00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:22.850
[Applause]

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:28.860
&gt;&gt;Dr. Colby: Thank you, Jen.

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:34.110
Today is an incredibly
important day for our civilization.

00:02:34.110 --> 00:02:38.100
And it's important
because we stand right at the point of transition

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:42.430
between
the age of information and the age of personalization.

00:02:42.430 --> 00:02:44.930
We're moving from this information age where
we now have

00:02:44.930 --> 00:02:49.620
an unprecedented amount of access to information.

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:53.520
Basically, our world's accumulated information
as

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:57.180
knowledge accessible to anyone and any time
from anywhere

00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:58.980
for practically no cost.

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:03.770
And we're moving from access to
this information from this generic information

00:03:03.770 --> 00:03:07.590
to now
personalizing it and making it about a unique

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:11.650
person --
about each of us in unique ways.

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:15.450
And the fundamental
underpinning of how information is made to

00:03:15.450 --> 00:03:18.960
be
personalized on how each of us is unique is

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:21.260
our genes.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:23.250
And that's what I'm going to talk about today
-- gaining

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:29.260
access to our genes through genetic testing,
understanding what that means, and then using

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:33.170
that
information to personalize products and services.

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:34.830
Since
I'm a doctor, I'm going to talk about how

00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:38.100
we can use that
information to personalize health care.

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:41.810
This is
applicable to really any product and service

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:43.390
that we
could think of.

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:47.990
And in the future, we're going to start
to see a genetically-tailored world that all

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:52.150
products and
services are going to start to be tailored

00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:53.150
to our genes.

00:03:53.150 --> 00:03:56.060
They're going to be personalized.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:59.760
So to begin, I'm going
to walk you through an example that we're

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:02.160
all going to
participate in.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:04.470
For some of you, it may help to close
your eyes.

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:09.460
For others, let's just imagine that we're
standing in a darkroom.

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:14.510
And the room is so dark, we
can't even see our hand in front of our face.

00:04:14.510 --> 00:04:17.410
All of a
sudden, we feel something come up and kick

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:20.220
us in the back
of the leg.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:25.330
We turn around, we try to defend ourselves,
but we can't, because we don't know what's

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:28.439
attacking us,
we don't know when it's going to come again

00:04:28.439 --> 00:04:31.850
and we feel
something go and punch us in the stomach.

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:34.550
We try to
defend ourselves again and we can't and again

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:35.969
we get hit
in the head.

00:04:35.969 --> 00:04:41.919
Now, I know this seems like an awkward
situation, but this is actually the current

00:04:41.919 --> 00:04:45.580
state of
health care that we're in practically the

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:47.220
dark ages.

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:49.840
We
don't know what diseases may lay ahead.

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:54.099
We don't know what
we may be faced with and we don't know when

00:04:54.099 --> 00:04:56.330
they may come
and attack us.

00:04:56.330 --> 00:05:01.889
Now, imagine that we're back in that room
again, it's very dark, we can't see, and somebody

00:05:01.889 --> 00:05:05.039
places something into our hands, a tool.

00:05:05.039 --> 00:05:07.370
But we don't
know whether that tool is going to help us,

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:10.669
whether we'll be
able to use that tool to defend ourselves

00:05:10.669 --> 00:05:14.550
or potentially that tool is going to harm
us.

00:05:14.550 --> 00:05:17.050
And that's the
current state of many of the treatments that

00:05:17.050 --> 00:05:20.840
we receive, a lot of the medications that
are prescribed to us.

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:22.990
We don't know if
they're going to be effective.

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:26.919
We don't know if they're
potentially going to harm us.

00:05:26.919 --> 00:05:30.419
And the person who hands
you that tool in that room is your doctor,

00:05:30.419 --> 00:05:31.940
your
physician.

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:33.479
And their eyesight--.

00:05:33.479 --> 00:05:36.879
Our eyesight is not
much better than yours.

00:05:36.879 --> 00:05:40.009
That we can't really make out
what's ahead.

00:05:40.009 --> 00:05:46.280
We use family history to try to guess at
what diseases you may be predisposed to.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:48.840
We ask you
questions like, "have you ever had a an allergic

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:49.969
reaction
before?"

00:05:49.969 --> 00:05:54.729
To try to guess at medications that we don't
want to give you.

00:05:54.729 --> 00:05:57.440
But other than that, our eyesight is
really not much better.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:00.449
We can make out shadows, but we
don't really know what is there.

00:06:00.449 --> 00:06:03.139
We don't know what
diseases lay ahead for you.

00:06:03.139 --> 00:06:07.599
And because of that, we
can't really prevent anything from coming

00:06:07.599 --> 00:06:09.520
and attacking
you.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:15.439
Now, we talked about this model, so health
care in terms of

00:06:15.439 --> 00:06:18.070
being in the dark ages.

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:22.529
What predictive medicine does,
which is combining genetic testing with the

00:06:22.529 --> 00:06:25.629
personalized
prevention of disease is, it turns the light

00:06:25.629 --> 00:06:26.629
on.

00:06:26.629 --> 00:06:30.400
It
allows us, through genetic testing, to examine

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:33.610
an
individual's genes to see what diseases they

00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:36.139
may be
predisposed to.

00:06:36.139 --> 00:06:40.009
And then to add preventions before those
diseases ever manifest.

00:06:40.009 --> 00:06:44.900
So it's turning the light on in
the room, allowing us to see what's lurking

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:49.460
in those
shadows, allows us to best take preemptive

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:53.340
measures, to
either prevent that disease from ever attacking

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:54.340
us.

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:56.810
Or if
we see it coming towards us because that light

00:06:56.810 --> 00:07:01.449
now is on
in the room, we could take steps to make sure

00:07:01.449 --> 00:07:07.460
that it has
the smallest amount of impact upon us as possible.

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:10.680
And
also genetic testing allows us to know whether

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:12.740
medications, whether certain treatments, even
lifestyle

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:16.930
modifications as we'll discuss, whether those
will help

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:20.430
slow down or prevent disease.

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:26.439
So, we're moving now from
standing in this very dark room to turning

00:07:26.439 --> 00:07:27.439
on the light.

00:07:27.439 --> 00:07:30.370
To be able to turn on the light through genetic
testing

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:32.569
and predictive medicine.

00:07:32.569 --> 00:07:34.759
So let's move on to the next example and actually
walk

00:07:34.759 --> 00:07:38.080
through a person's life and see how this could
impact

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:39.189
somebody today.

00:07:39.189 --> 00:07:44.800
Because everything we're going to
discuss in this entire talk is possible today.

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:47.249
So let's
say today a baby is born.

00:07:47.249 --> 00:07:49.069
Baby Emily.

00:07:49.069 --> 00:07:52.620
She's born
completely healthy, lives a normal childhood,

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:55.259
teenage years,
no problem.

00:07:55.259 --> 00:07:56.840
She gets through her 20s.

00:07:56.840 --> 00:07:57.840
She's fine.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:07:58.840
She
turns 30.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:05.600
She begins to start a family and all of a
sudden she goes and has a massive heart attack.

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:08.300
She's in
the intensive care unit for about two weeks

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:10.490
and then
unfortunately she dies.

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:17.030
Now, her parent -- I'm sorry --
her physicians did absolutely nothing wrong.

00:08:17.030 --> 00:08:20.669
So the
physicians practice medicine as they're taught.

00:08:20.669 --> 00:08:27.210
That
they treated her like a generic patient.

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:30.460
Throughout her
teenage years, throughout her 20s, hardly

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:33.761
ever does a
doctor closely examine somebody's heart, because

00:08:33.761 --> 00:08:37.600
most
people that age -- their hearts are fine.

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:40.090
But Emily is
unique as most of us are.

00:08:40.090 --> 00:08:41.430
She was unique.

00:08:41.430 --> 00:08:43.960
She contained
genes that were predisposing her to early

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:47.450
onset heart
attack and her doctors just had no idea.

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:50.130
They were
standing in that dark room.

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:53.260
And that's why a heart
attack was able to go and manifest.

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:54.950
Her cholesterol built up.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:58.890
It was never detected and she had that heart
attack.

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:00.620
So
now we have tremendous heartache.

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:03.290
Her family has lost a
loved one.

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:09.410
We have doctors who were powerless to protect
their patient's life.

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:13.380
And we also have society that now
has spent a tremendous amount of money on

00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:18.210
this ICU care
in the intensive care unit and lost a productive

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:22.370
member
of their community at the end.

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:25.180
So let's say slightly
different scenario.

00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:27.750
Emily is in the intensive care unit.

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:30.870
She's able to be saved and her doctors go
and prescribe a

00:09:30.870 --> 00:09:31.880
medication.

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:36.680
A medication that they give to a lot of
people in this situation.

00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:39.830
And they treat Emily again
like a generic patient.

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:42.019
They start her at 5 milligrams.

00:09:42.019 --> 00:09:45.760
Everybody who receives this blood thinner
receives it at

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:47.200
5 milligrams.

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:48.780
And most of us are used to that.

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:51.820
When our
doctor prescribes us medications, it's at

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:54.880
the same dose
that you know they've given to the last person

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:57.080
and
they'll give to the next person.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:01.750
But, for Emily, she's
extremely sensitive to this medication.

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:03.470
Her doctors
had no idea.

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:08.080
They didn't want to cause any harm, but
they thinned her blood so much with that 5

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:11.040
milligrams
that she ended up bleeding into her brain

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:13.760
and she died
again.

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:16.200
So again, we have the loss of life, we have
the

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.200
heartache and we have the loss to society
in terms of

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:23.080
spending a tremendous amount of money and
now actually

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:27.650
causing more harm than good.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:31.170
So now, the model of
predictive medicine -- of using genetic testing

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:33.160
-- to
predict disease.

00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:38.070
We could go all the way to when Emily
is born.

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:40.280
Genetic testing is so simple now, doesn't
even

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:42.150
require any blood.

00:10:42.150 --> 00:10:45.720
So her parents choose to have genetic
testing for Emily.

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:49.500
They collect some of her saliva with
her pediatrician.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:54.940
They send that for testing and analysis, which
we'll talk about later.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:59.320
And the doctor gets back the
report and sees that Emily contains genes

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:01.830
that predispose
her to early onset heart attack.

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:05.720
And again, this is
possible now.

00:11:05.720 --> 00:11:07.410
So the doctor makes note of that.

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:10.880
There's
not much to be done right at that age when

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:15.230
she's a baby,
but when she enters her teenage years, her

00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:17.500
doctors do
something differently.

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:21.170
They start to pay attention to
her heart, because that light has been turned

00:11:21.170 --> 00:11:22.810
on in the
room.

00:11:22.810 --> 00:11:26.580
They know heart disease is lurking in the
shadows.

00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:28.870
So they start doing blood tests, they start
monitoring

00:11:28.870 --> 00:11:30.500
her cholesterol levels.

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:33.070
Different biomarkers.

00:11:33.070 --> 00:11:37.180
And when she gets
to about 18 or 19, they see that her cholesterol

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:39.540
levels
start to go up.

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:45.170
So the doctors go and work with her --
go over her genetic report in terms of lifestyle

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:47.130
modifications.

00:11:47.130 --> 00:11:49.310
Let's not start medications right now,
they say.

00:11:49.310 --> 00:11:51.980
Let's focus on lifestyle modifications.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:55.720
They're able to go tailor her cardiovascular
exercise to

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:56.820
her genes.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:02.550
So that she's able to optimize what are going
to be the most effective exercises for her.

00:12:02.550 --> 00:12:05.730
They're also
able to go and start to tailor some of her

00:12:05.730 --> 00:12:06.730
nutrition.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.260
So
they talk about some of the generic things

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:13.340
we're told in terms of
low fat diet, staying away from refined sugars.

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:16.460
But they
also tell her based upon her genetic profile,

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:20.780
eating a
specific type of vegetable, cruciferous vegetables,

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:24.020
are
likely to be beneficial to her in cutting

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:25.980
down her heart
attack risk.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:30.440
And they also see from her genetic report
that she's likely not to like the taste of

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:32.190
these
vegetables.

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:37.710
Based upon taste bud genes, those vegetables
are likely to taste really bitter to her.

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:42.850
So they tell her
different methods to still eat those vegetables

00:12:42.850 --> 00:12:45.330
but avoid
that bitter taste such as mixing them with

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:46.970
other foods.

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:49.840
So as you see they're completely tailoring
these

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:52.730
lifestyle recommendations to her genes to
make them as

00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:55.510
effective as possible.

00:12:55.510 --> 00:12:59.810
So now Emily is able to go and
integrate this into her lifestyle.

00:12:59.810 --> 00:13:04.260
She slows down the
progression of disease significantly.

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:09.950
But then in her
mid 30s, her doctors are still conscientiously

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:11.500
monitoring
her blood.

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:15.620
They see her cholesterol levels increasing
again.

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:18.640
So at that time, her doctors say, "all right,
we

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:22.690
have to go and start integrating some medications."

00:13:22.690 --> 00:13:26.990
The
genes were -- we were able to slow down the

00:13:26.990 --> 00:13:29.530
process but
now we need medications.

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:31.610
We need something stronger.

00:13:31.610 --> 00:13:34.440
So
you look at the genetic profile that was taken

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:37.280
when Emily
was just a child.

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:41.580
And they see that she's very sensitive
to a medication they're about to prescribe.

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:47.130
So instead
of giving 5 milligrams, they give 0.5 milligrams.

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:48.930
Emily
is able to avoid a heart attack.

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:54.300
She's able to raise a
family, have grandchildren, and live a full

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.380
life.

00:13:56.380 --> 00:13:58.870
Now
the doctors are able to focus in on what's

00:13:58.870 --> 00:14:02.340
important for
Emily and also provide the most effective

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:04.070
preventions and
treatments.

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:06.190
So they've been a success, too.

00:14:06.190 --> 00:14:09.620
And now our
society has gained a productive member of

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:11.760
the community
throughout her entire life.

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:15.630
And they focus all their
health care spending on that which matters

00:14:15.630 --> 00:14:19.670
most and that which is going to be most
effective.

00:14:19.670 --> 00:14:21.810
So that is what genetic testing now allows
--

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:25.240
it allows us to go turn on that light for
health care.

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:29.050
It
allows us to move from our current model of

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:34.290
health care,
which is really more like sick care.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:37.130
Most of us just
wait until we get sick and then we see a doctor.

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:40.510
We wait
for a disease to occur and then we go and

00:14:40.510 --> 00:14:44.540
we diagnose and
doctors hope that they could treat.

00:14:44.540 --> 00:14:48.500
But what this new
model -- this genetic testing, this personalization

00:14:48.500 --> 00:14:54.650
of healthcare -- allows us to do is actually
go and move to a different paradigm where

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:58.960
we focus on the
proactive personalized prevention of disease

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:03.800
throughout a
person's life.

00:15:03.800 --> 00:15:10.930
Now, we've been talking about genetic
testing.

00:15:10.930 --> 00:15:13.280
It's a bit nebulous to people in terms of
what

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:16.390
exactly genetic testing is.

00:15:16.390 --> 00:15:20.000
And genetic testing is
really a generic term people use to refer

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.230
to three things
or three components of genetic technology.

00:15:24.230 --> 00:15:27.810
The first is
testing, so that's the acquisition of raw

00:15:27.810 --> 00:15:28.810
data.

00:15:28.810 --> 00:15:32.680
The
second is analysis, or clinical analysis,

00:15:32.680 --> 00:15:35.910
that's
transitioning that data, translating it from

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:40.610
this raw
data to an actionable information state.

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:41.900
And the third
is reporting.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:44.550
It's actually delivering that to the end
user.

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:47.300
We'll talk about each one of those now.

00:15:47.300 --> 00:16:00.820
So the
first component -- just get to the slide -- [pause]

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:16.380
okay great, thank
you.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:18.740
So the first component is testing.

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:22.870
And testing is
acquiring all the raw data -- all the letters

00:16:22.870 --> 00:16:24.840
of our
genetic code.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:27.670
And this involves a lot of hardware.

00:16:27.670 --> 00:16:31.810
So
it involves laboratory function.

00:16:31.810 --> 00:16:35.010
And I'm going to talk
about two other types of technology that allows

00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:38.590
us to
undergo this genetic testing.

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:41.010
Let's take a step back and
think about where genetic testing was about

00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:42.620
ten years ago.

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:46.750
So
ten years ago to look at one single gene may

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:50.810
have cost 5,
10, even 20,000 dollars and it would have

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:53.520
taken months
for that to be turned around.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:58.250
And almost always, you had
to go and give blood; so it was invasive.

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:01.590
Now with this
new technology that we'll discuss first, -- called

00:17:01.590 --> 00:17:06.360
a DNA chip
or microarray -- that's a generic term.

00:17:06.360 --> 00:17:09.919
Now with this new
technology, we don't have to look at just

00:17:09.919 --> 00:17:10.919
one gene.

00:17:10.919 --> 00:17:12.999
We
can look at thousands of genes all at the

00:17:12.999 --> 00:17:16.720
same time for
just a few hundred dollars.

00:17:16.720 --> 00:17:21.769
So it's been a major
inflection point in terms of how much we're

00:17:21.769 --> 00:17:27.319
able to do
for much more cost effective price point.

00:17:27.319 --> 00:17:31.100
And also all
we have to do right now is really use saliva.

00:17:31.100 --> 00:17:33.779
We do not
need to use blood anymore.

00:17:33.779 --> 00:17:36.509
So it's become non-invasive.

00:17:36.509 --> 00:17:43.029
And this is a picture of one type of gene
chip, of a DNA

00:17:43.029 --> 00:17:44.029
chip.

00:17:44.029 --> 00:17:52.409
This is the one that I spent about six years
creating called the Nexus DNA chip.

00:17:52.409 --> 00:17:55.570
This is the actual
chip itself.

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:59.279
So one of these is used to process 12
different samples.

00:17:59.279 --> 00:18:02.440
And you could come up and take a look
at this after, but this is just so that you

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:12.000
guys have an
idea of the scale that it's quite small.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.679
And what this
does is, it allows us to look at thousands

00:18:14.679 --> 00:18:17.370
of genes all at
the same time.

00:18:17.370 --> 00:18:21.019
And it skips over all of the irrelevant
information.

00:18:21.019 --> 00:18:23.299
So this is one gene.

00:18:23.299 --> 00:18:26.690
And you could think
of all the letters -- so all those are different

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:29.279
GPS
coordinates.

00:18:29.279 --> 00:18:34.429
And only those that are in red are known to
be associated with some clinical state.

00:18:34.429 --> 00:18:35.940
They have some
relevancy.

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:38.770
All the other data is just extraneous.

00:18:38.770 --> 00:18:40.950
Even
if we had it, we wouldn't do anything with

00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:41.950
it.

00:18:41.950 --> 00:18:45.929
So what a
DNA chip allows us to do is hone in -- zero

00:18:45.929 --> 00:18:50.269
in -- on
those that are red and test those in the individual.

00:18:50.269 --> 00:18:54.330
So we're
testing several different letters in one gene.

00:18:54.330 --> 00:18:56.370
Then we
move on to the next gene and the next and

00:18:56.370 --> 00:18:57.370
the next.

00:18:57.370 --> 00:19:00.169
So
we're skipping over all that is superfluous.

00:19:00.169 --> 00:19:02.779
We're
focusing in on that which is most important.

00:19:02.779 --> 00:19:06.960
Now, the Nexus DNA chip is
important for predictive medicine purposes.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:09.200
There are
different chips out there.

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:13.919
This one is specific for
really protecting a person's health, for preventing

00:19:13.919 --> 00:19:15.970
disease risk and then finding out what's really
going to

00:19:15.970 --> 00:19:19.590
be the most effective preventions.

00:19:19.590 --> 00:19:24.289
And this has really
unlocked this new era -- this genetic revolution.

00:19:24.289 --> 00:19:28.080
Our
ability to move towards personalization because

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:32.360
of this
technology which is just a few hundred dollars.

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:35.840
Now,
there's a new technology that's currently

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:36.840
in development.

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:40.020
It's moving along quite rapidly called whole
genome

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:42.720
sequencing.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:45.710
Many of us are probably familiar with the
human genome project.

00:19:45.710 --> 00:19:47.440
That took about ten years.

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:51.070
It was
completed in 2003.

00:19:51.070 --> 00:19:54.049
And it cost about 3 billion dollars
to accomplish.

00:19:54.049 --> 00:19:56.990
Required an international team of
scientists.

00:19:56.990 --> 00:19:59.799
So 2003, 3 billion dollars.

00:19:59.799 --> 00:20:02.990
And that
was all to sequence a single person.

00:20:02.990 --> 00:20:06.629
And whole genome
sequencing mean you're getting 6 billion letters

00:20:06.629 --> 00:20:08.650
per
person.

00:20:08.650 --> 00:20:12.190
So the DNA chip may acquire tens of thousands
to

00:20:12.190 --> 00:20:13.980
millions of letters.

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:16.670
This new technology requires every
single letter.

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:19.539
So it acquires both the black and the
red.

00:20:19.539 --> 00:20:20.730
It doesn't distinguish.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:22.539
It just gets the entire
sequence.

00:20:22.539 --> 00:20:26.059
And that's 6 billion letters per person.

00:20:26.059 --> 00:20:29.379
So
what costs 3 billion dollars and took ten

00:20:29.379 --> 00:20:35.490
years and ended
in 2003 today could be done for 4,000 dollars

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:38.419
and takes
about a month.

00:20:38.419 --> 00:20:43.720
That's projected to come down quite
rapidly all the way to 500, 100 dollar mark

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:48.059
and soon
under a day, maybe even an hour where we're

00:20:48.059 --> 00:20:52.019
able to go
accumulate all this data.

00:20:52.019 --> 00:20:56.700
As we see from the DNA chip
where it's getting tens of thousands to millions

00:20:56.700 --> 00:21:01.669
of relevant data points
to whole genome sequencing that getting 6

00:21:01.669 --> 00:21:03.830
billion, it's
an avalanche of data.

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:08.990
So tremendous amount of raw data
we have to deal with right now.

00:21:08.990 --> 00:21:13.519
And that's where the
next component comes in that's clinical analysis.

00:21:13.519 --> 00:21:17.440
So
that's why moving from testing to analysis

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:18.440
is really
important.

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:20.380
And we'll talk about that in a moment.

00:21:20.380 --> 00:21:24.550
But
first, how relevant is whole genome sequencing

00:21:24.550 --> 00:21:27.000
to us?

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.159
And this chart shows the decreasing cost.

00:21:29.159 --> 00:21:32.730
So the lines
that are in red and black and green are different

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:36.119
costs
of this technology of whole genome sequencing.

00:21:36.119 --> 00:21:39.039
The line
that's in blue is a number of people who have

00:21:39.039 --> 00:21:41.419
had their
genome sequenced.

00:21:41.419 --> 00:21:44.320
Number of just individuals.

00:21:44.320 --> 00:21:48.749
So by the
end of this year we'll be somewhere around

00:21:48.749 --> 00:21:53.399
50,000; it's
projected to be around that.

00:21:53.399 --> 00:21:59.789
And we think to about 2014
or so we're looking at closer to 10 to 100

00:21:59.789 --> 00:22:00.789
million.

00:22:00.789 --> 00:22:03.129
We
look at 2020, we're looking at close to a

00:22:03.129 --> 00:22:05.140
billion
genomes.

00:22:05.140 --> 00:22:10.230
A billion people having their entire sequence
deduced.

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:13.950
So a billion people and 6 billion letters
per

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:15.380
person.

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:19.610
So it's just a tremendous avalanche of data.

00:22:19.610 --> 00:22:22.059
And now, the question arises, "What do we
do with all

00:22:22.059 --> 00:22:23.059
that data?

00:22:23.059 --> 00:22:25.450
How do we make sense of that?"

00:22:25.450 --> 00:22:28.690
And that's
really what my team and I specialize in.

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:32.639
It's clinical
analysis and reporting of this tremendous

00:22:32.639 --> 00:22:37.669
amount of raw
data that's now able to be accumulated using

00:22:37.669 --> 00:22:39.740
this new
technology.

00:22:39.740 --> 00:22:45.759
And what clinical analysis does is, it
translates the data from just raw data into

00:22:45.759 --> 00:22:48.710
actionable
meaningful information.

00:22:48.710 --> 00:22:52.730
It allows value to be attributed
to them.

00:22:52.730 --> 00:22:56.130
Because without analysis, all those letters
of

00:22:56.130 --> 00:22:58.620
a person's genome are really nothing more
than a

00:22:58.620 --> 00:23:00.460
high-tech paper weight.

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:04.760
That's -- it's not even a paper
weight because you can fit that on a small

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:05.760
thumb drive.

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:07.559
So
it's quite light.

00:23:07.559 --> 00:23:13.409
None of that is important to a
person's health unless that data is translated

00:23:13.409 --> 00:23:15.039
into
information.

00:23:15.039 --> 00:23:20.060
I'm going to go through one example of a
clinical analysis technology just so that

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:23.269
you have some
idea of what I'm talking about when I refer

00:23:23.269 --> 00:23:27.220
to analysis.

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:30.620
Let's think back to the baby Emily example
that she has

00:23:30.620 --> 00:23:34.019
genetic testing, she's found to be at increased
risk of a

00:23:34.019 --> 00:23:42.929
heart attack, then I also mention that different
medications are analyzed.

00:23:42.929 --> 00:23:47.249
So that means that different
genes are looked at after a heart attack risk

00:23:47.249 --> 00:23:48.860
is
detected.

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:54.379
Different genes are analyzed in relation to
different preventions and treatments associated

00:23:54.379 --> 00:23:56.480
with
heart attack.

00:23:56.480 --> 00:24:00.090
Different lifestyle modifications -- like
the cruciferous vegetables and whether that

00:24:00.090 --> 00:24:04.159
taste that
Emily is going to enjoy the taste or not,

00:24:04.159 --> 00:24:06.409
those genes are
analyzed.

00:24:06.409 --> 00:24:11.480
So it's a whole another set, all different
sets of genes are then analyzed after that

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:16.749
initial center
node, that center disease.

00:24:16.749 --> 00:24:21.649
And we could see a flowchart
here that goes first rounds, a risk of heart

00:24:21.649 --> 00:24:23.210
attack is
deduced.

00:24:23.210 --> 00:24:26.139
Then the reflex analysis comes in.

00:24:26.139 --> 00:24:29.350
This is all
software based, so we move from the testing

00:24:29.350 --> 00:24:32.490
which is
hardware to now the clinical analysis which

00:24:32.490 --> 00:24:34.389
is software.

00:24:34.389 --> 00:24:40.530
So the software is doing this and it's programmed
specifically to be able to do this analysis.

00:24:40.530 --> 00:24:43.289
It moves
from this first round to this second round

00:24:43.289 --> 00:24:45.429
which looks at
different medications whether they're going

00:24:45.429 --> 00:24:48.070
to be
effective, whether somebody is going to be

00:24:48.070 --> 00:24:49.870
sensitive to
them.

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:52.940
It also looks at lifestyle modifications.

00:24:52.940 --> 00:24:55.720
We
could even now start to provide someone information

00:24:55.720 --> 00:24:59.249
whether surgery -- like a coronary artery
bypass graft-- is

00:24:59.249 --> 00:25:01.049
going to be effective or not.

00:25:01.049 --> 00:25:05.100
That's still in the
preliminary stages while these other information

00:25:05.100 --> 00:25:09.519
now is
in the much more advanced stage.

00:25:09.519 --> 00:25:12.350
And then the third
round of analysis we could go even deeper.

00:25:12.350 --> 00:25:14.539
So we could
start to look at specific dosing for some

00:25:14.539 --> 00:25:15.539
of the
medications.

00:25:15.539 --> 00:25:21.009
That where we look at whether the person is
going to like the taste of vegetables.

00:25:21.009 --> 00:25:23.960
Look at things that
are associated with exercise.

00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:28.299
Reflex analysis really
goes as deep as needed in order to get all

00:25:28.299 --> 00:25:30.330
of these
reflexes -- all of these different sets of

00:25:30.330 --> 00:25:32.299
genes
analyzed.

00:25:32.299 --> 00:25:40.389
And the whole purpose is to make that analysis
now integrated, which makes it much more actionable.

00:25:40.389 --> 00:25:42.580
And
we'll see that as it's presented in the genetic

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:44.980
report in
a few minutes.

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:48.600
And this allows us to analyze a
tremendous amount of data all at once, so

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:50.249
all together.

00:25:50.249 --> 00:25:52.711
Instead of thinking about it in a 2-dimensional
way, this

00:25:52.711 --> 00:25:56.870
allows us to analyze things 3-dimensionally.

00:25:56.870 --> 00:26:00.999
And this is
computer software that we created to enable

00:26:00.999 --> 00:26:02.919
this reflex
analysis.

00:26:02.919 --> 00:26:06.440
So that enables us to go and set up these
types of

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:09.679
reflexes, underlying each of the nodes that
you see is a

00:26:09.679 --> 00:26:14.659
whole set of diseases, whole sets of algorithms
for

00:26:14.659 --> 00:26:16.820
traits or medications or conditions.

00:26:16.820 --> 00:26:21.259
But this allows us
our IT system to know to analyze one then

00:26:21.259 --> 00:26:24.350
to reflex to
another one and then potentially another one

00:26:24.350 --> 00:26:27.519
and another
one.

00:26:27.519 --> 00:26:30.539
So we've talked about testing.

00:26:30.539 --> 00:26:33.809
So the acquiring
the raw data.

00:26:33.809 --> 00:26:40.489
And we talked about analysis -- moving
that data into useful, understandable information.

00:26:40.489 --> 00:26:43.610
And
the third part is really key.

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:49.570
Because without proper
reporting, that testing which may be extremely

00:26:49.570 --> 00:26:52.760
accurate
and the analysis which may be beautiful, without

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:55.960
proper
reporting, then it's all useless.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:57.460
It's all wasted.

00:26:57.460 --> 00:27:00.909
The
end-user can't easily understand what that

00:27:00.909 --> 00:27:04.580
data means and
can't integrate that beneficially into their

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:07.450
lives, then
all that usefulness is lost.

00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:10.669
The third step is
reporting.

00:27:10.669 --> 00:27:14.429
And there are many different types of report
formats out there.

00:27:14.429 --> 00:27:16.600
One is not better than the other.

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:20.090
It's just really dependent upon what you,
the end-user,

00:27:20.090 --> 00:27:22.309
wants to get out of genetic testing.

00:27:22.309 --> 00:27:25.559
So I'm going to go
over one of the types of reports.

00:27:25.559 --> 00:27:28.779
This is the report
that my team and I have come up with over

00:27:28.779 --> 00:27:30.929
the past five
years.

00:27:30.929 --> 00:27:32.701
But it's just as important to note that there
are

00:27:32.701 --> 00:27:37.269
many different types of report formats that
are out there now.

00:27:37.269 --> 00:27:43.019
So this is a report format for heart attack
risk.

00:27:43.019 --> 00:27:47.860
This
is the actual report that's printed.

00:27:47.860 --> 00:27:51.230
So this is
delivered -- it would be delivered let's say

00:27:51.230 --> 00:27:53.269
to Emily's
pediatrician.

00:27:53.269 --> 00:27:56.659
And this is a report page that talks about
heart attack.

00:27:56.659 --> 00:28:01.019
It's actually two pages because there's so
many medications now associated with heart

00:28:01.019 --> 00:28:04.389
disease that
we could provide information about when we

00:28:04.389 --> 00:28:05.710
do genetic
testing.

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:10.940
So right at the top, we see three gauges.

00:28:10.940 --> 00:28:13.869
The
gauge right in the center is risk.

00:28:13.869 --> 00:28:16.590
So this person is at
high risk.

00:28:16.590 --> 00:28:19.769
And it says specifically about 67 percent
risk.

00:28:19.769 --> 00:28:22.840
We like to focus more on the qualitative on
these

00:28:22.840 --> 00:28:23.840
zones.

00:28:23.840 --> 00:28:27.590
So they're in the zone of high risk.

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:30.649
And that is
based upon analysis many different genes.

00:28:30.649 --> 00:28:34.299
And it's also
compared right below it to what's called generic

00:28:34.299 --> 00:28:35.830
population risk.

00:28:35.830 --> 00:28:41.070
That's the everyday risk for a person
if they have no idea what their genes contain.

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:44.279
It's just
taken off of mass population studies and say

00:28:44.279 --> 00:28:48.239
how many
people around this age with this ethnicity

00:28:48.239 --> 00:28:52.610
with this
gender are likely to have this disease?

00:28:52.610 --> 00:28:56.529
And for heart
attacks, for a Caucasian male, it's around

00:28:56.529 --> 00:28:58.620
47%
lifetime risk.

00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:03.100
For this person based upon their genes,
it's closer to 70 percent risk.

00:29:03.100 --> 00:29:05.129
So they're at high risk.

00:29:05.129 --> 00:29:06.580
Now there are two other gauges.

00:29:06.580 --> 00:29:11.690
A gauge on the left is
the clinical significance gauge.

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:15.250
And that's there so
that a person understands, "is this information

00:29:15.250 --> 00:29:17.570
even
relevant to their health?"

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:21.200
