a gene -- they haven't done genetic testing
on him -- but

00:43:36.039 --> 00:43:41.119
very likely this condition was caused by genetic
abnormality.

00:43:41.119 --> 00:43:47.690
So he had this underlying condition,
dilated cardiomyopathy, that went undiagnosed.

00:43:47.690 --> 00:43:49.510
And
that's what led to his death.

00:43:49.510 --> 00:43:53.599
Now, I frequently test
patients for this condition and a large number

00:43:53.599 --> 00:43:56.460
of other
preventable sudden cardiac death.

00:43:56.460 --> 00:44:01.630
So I test them on a
genetic level using this Nexus DNA chip, using

00:44:01.630 --> 00:44:03.190
just
saliva.

00:44:03.190 --> 00:44:05.859
At the same time we're looking at all the
risks

00:44:05.859 --> 00:44:08.160
for different types of cancers, heart disease.

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:10.950
We're
also looking at preventable causes of sudden

00:44:10.950 --> 00:44:11.950
death.

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:15.279
Now
I've detected dilated cardiomyopathy in patients.

00:44:15.279 --> 00:44:17.839
I've
detected other sudden death diseases that

00:44:17.839 --> 00:44:18.839
are
preventable.

00:44:18.839 --> 00:44:24.990
They all have complicated names like long
QT syndrome and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy

00:44:24.990 --> 00:44:27.190
and
arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:30.970
So I've detected these in people.

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:33.329
They go and they see a cardiologist and prevention.

00:44:33.329 --> 00:44:35.320
It's
very simple preventions.

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:36.910
Usually just medications.

00:44:36.910 --> 00:44:39.520
Low
cost medications are enacted.

00:44:39.520 --> 00:44:42.020
And sudden death is
avoided.

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:47.690
So in Wes Leonard's case one thing that could
have saved him was if he had genetic testing.

00:44:47.690 --> 00:44:51.730
As you see, It's not like he could have waited
for that.

00:44:51.730 --> 00:44:52.970
One year, five years.

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:56.849
He needed it last year.

00:44:56.849 --> 00:45:00.880
So this is not only applicable
to preventable sudden cardiac at the time,

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:03.460
it's also
applicable to all different types of cancer

00:45:03.460 --> 00:45:08.930
from breast
cancer, colon cancer, prostate cancer, skin

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:10.620
cancer, such
as melanoma.

00:45:10.620 --> 00:45:12.910
Applicable to heart disease.

00:45:12.910 --> 00:45:16.240
It's even
applicable to Alzheimer's disease where we

00:45:16.240 --> 00:45:20.359
have different
interventions we can enact throughout life

00:45:20.359 --> 00:45:23.589
which has been
shown to decrease either the risk of that

00:45:23.589 --> 00:45:27.910
disease or
greatly delay its onset.

00:45:27.910 --> 00:45:30.260
So we have that ability today.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:33.910
Now, the third reason why this is so important
-- why we

00:45:33.910 --> 00:45:39.880
need this now -- is to save our future generations.

00:45:39.880 --> 00:45:42.339
So
genetic testing now allows us to identify

00:45:42.339 --> 00:45:45.829
what diseases
we carry in our genes.

00:45:45.829 --> 00:45:49.039
And by "carry," I mean we may not
have that disease.

00:45:49.039 --> 00:45:51.059
We most likely don't have that
disease.

00:45:51.059 --> 00:45:53.329
We have no way of knowing that we carry it.

00:45:53.329 --> 00:45:55.200
These are rare diseases.

00:45:55.200 --> 00:46:01.160
Rare recessive diseases like
cystic fibrosis, Tay-Sach's disease, sickle

00:46:01.160 --> 00:46:03.000
cell anemia.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:07.020
So we have no idea that we may carry these
diseases, but

00:46:07.020 --> 00:46:09.380
if we have a child with somebody who also
carries the

00:46:09.380 --> 00:46:12.960
same disease, then there's a high likelihood
that the

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:15.660
child will have that disease.

00:46:15.660 --> 00:46:21.950
That's why we see often
people will have a child and that child will

00:46:21.950 --> 00:46:24.551
have a
disease and the parents will say, "I had no

00:46:24.551 --> 00:46:27.730
idea that I
carried this.

00:46:27.730 --> 00:46:30.599
It's never manifested in my family before.

00:46:30.599 --> 00:46:32.040
This is the first time."

00:46:32.040 --> 00:46:36.890
But through genetic testing, we
can now identify what diseases we carry.

00:46:36.890 --> 00:46:40.020
And geneticists
postulate that each person probably carries

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:42.590
three or four
diseases.

00:46:42.590 --> 00:46:46.550
Each of us in this room right now are carrying
three to four rare diseases.

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:47.839
Do you know which ones they
are?

00:46:47.839 --> 00:46:50.500
Do you know your spouse -- that person you're
going

00:46:50.500 --> 00:46:55.310
to have a child with -- also carries those
diseases.

00:46:55.310 --> 00:46:59.549
Using
gene chip technology --so this Nexus DNA chip--

00:46:59.549 --> 00:47:01.700
, at first we
could screen for a handful.

00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:03.740
Now we could screen for
hundreds.

00:47:03.740 --> 00:47:06.960
Just recently we enabled this to gene for
over

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:07.960
1,000 rare diseases.

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:11.290
Over 1,000 rare diseases all at the
same time.

00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:15.089
So we could start to identify who's carrying
what disease.

00:47:15.089 --> 00:47:17.140
Doesn't mean that anything's wrong with
the person.

00:47:17.140 --> 00:47:22.880
It just means that now they could take
proactive steps to protect their future generations.

00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:25.440
And
there are clear things they could do to protect

00:47:25.440 --> 00:47:28.400
their
future generations from inheriting a deadly

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:31.440
disease if
both they carry it and a spouse or whoever

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:36.160
they're going to have a
child with also carries that disease.

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:41.109
So it allows us to
save our health care system, save ourselves,

00:47:41.109 --> 00:47:43.859
and to save
future generations all today.

00:47:43.859 --> 00:47:48.000
And this is all possible
because we have this inflection point with

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:49.760
the technology.

00:47:49.760 --> 00:47:52.410
So the testing now has come down tremendously
in price.

00:47:52.410 --> 00:47:56.319
It's unlocked a way to access all of our genes.

00:47:56.319 --> 00:47:59.191
We have
ways to analyze and understand this, because

00:47:59.191 --> 00:48:01.250
we have 30
years of research.

00:48:01.250 --> 00:48:05.349
30 years of genetic research, of
looking at what genes are associated with

00:48:05.349 --> 00:48:06.920
what disease.

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:09.339
But
up until this technology that research has

00:48:09.339 --> 00:48:11.309
only been
relegated to the library.

00:48:11.309 --> 00:48:16.589
It's been published then it
goes into the library and it's not in use.

00:48:16.589 --> 00:48:19.040
But with this
technology now, we can move it out of the

00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:24.870
library and we
can make it all about one single person -- and

00:48:24.870 --> 00:48:26.940
that's
you.

00:48:26.940 --> 00:48:30.569
Thank you.

00:48:30.569 --> 00:48:35.430
Now, for some questions now?

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:36.460
Okay,
great

00:48:36.460 --> 00:48:40.529
&gt;&gt;Male #1: I'm curious about the rate among
the

00:48:40.529 --> 00:48:44.589
general population for which you think that
genetic

00:48:44.589 --> 00:48:48.470
testing can uncover, I guess, traits where
there's

00:48:48.470 --> 00:48:51.180
actionable advice for how to avoid disease.

00:48:51.180 --> 00:48:55.519
Like in
the case of cardiovascular disease, it's my

00:48:55.519 --> 00:48:58.890
understanding that there are some very rare
genetic

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:01.210
conditions that obviously it would be good
to test

00:49:01.210 --> 00:49:04.880
for, but more commonly it seems to be lifestyle
factors that are responsible.

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:05.880
&gt;&gt;Dr. Colby: Right.

00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:10.440
So there are two parts to that
question.

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:17.440
The question was asking about how many
really common diseases that we could do something

00:49:17.440 --> 00:49:19.309
about can we test for now?

00:49:19.309 --> 00:49:24.330
Is it only really just
rare diseases, possibly rare cardiovascular

00:49:24.330 --> 00:49:26.069
diseases can we test for.

00:49:26.069 --> 00:49:30.380
Are there really the common ones that we
could learn something about and have that

00:49:30.380 --> 00:49:32.220
be
actionable?

00:49:32.220 --> 00:49:36.079
And the answer is, there are actually a
large number right now that we can test for

00:49:36.079 --> 00:49:39.099
that are
common that is actionable.

00:49:39.099 --> 00:49:42.190
So we mentioned a lot of
different types of cancer from breast cancer,

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:45.440
colon
cancer, skin cancer, prostate cancer -- those

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:47.260
are
the big four.

00:49:47.260 --> 00:49:52.609
Except for lung cancer, which we know
is mainly attributed to smoking, that has

00:49:52.609 --> 00:49:56.130
much less
of a genetic effect.

00:49:56.130 --> 00:49:58.119
So those are all highly
actionable.

00:49:58.119 --> 00:50:02.250
If we even learn that a baby is at
risk, we can add preventions throughout life.

00:50:02.250 --> 00:50:04.339
For
cardiovascular disease, we've seen this example

00:50:04.339 --> 00:50:05.960
with heart attack.

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:07.970
That heart attack analysis where we saw that
person

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:09.510
was close to 70 percent.

00:50:09.510 --> 00:50:12.060
That was based on a large
number of genes.

00:50:12.060 --> 00:50:15.490
So we're not just looking at one
gene that has a small degree of risk.

00:50:15.490 --> 00:50:18.680
We're looking
at a lot of different genes, all of them have

00:50:18.680 --> 00:50:19.900
small risks.

00:50:19.900 --> 00:50:25.380
But together, when a person has a lot of different
small risks, that adds up and starts to build

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:27.089
upon
itself.

00:50:27.089 --> 00:50:32.569
So that does enable us to see very high
risks in people even if they don't have those

00:50:32.569 --> 00:50:34.180
rare
conditions.

00:50:34.180 --> 00:50:38.920
So even if they have just more common
forms of cholesterol build up and heart attack

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:40.109
risk.

00:50:40.109 --> 00:50:41.900
And the same thing with Alzheimer's disease.

00:50:41.900 --> 00:50:44.430
So
Alzheimer's disease has stolen the minds of

00:50:44.430 --> 00:50:46.680
an
entire generation.

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:49.790
And many of us fear that that
will be our fate.

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:57.119
We can now predict risk of
Alzheimer's disease and we could do that quite

00:50:57.119 --> 00:50:58.339
well.

00:50:58.339 --> 00:50:59.809
And we can enact preventions.

00:50:59.809 --> 00:51:04.309
So there's no way to
stop Alzheimer's disease, but there's ways,

00:51:04.309 --> 00:51:08.440
clear ways to
slow it down tremendously from ever occurring

00:51:08.440 --> 00:51:10.760
so
that if we just push it back ten years instead

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:13.390
of
affecting a person when they're 75 years,

00:51:13.390 --> 00:51:14.930
it starts at 85.

00:51:14.930 --> 00:51:18.849
That's a large number of golden years they
have to

00:51:18.849 --> 00:51:21.440
live that are healthy instead of sick.

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:27.450
And also with a large amount of money putting
towards research towards pharmaceuticals that

00:51:27.450 --> 00:51:31.690
are
working to actually cure diseases like Alzheimer's,

00:51:31.690 --> 00:51:34.850
those ten years may be all that a person needs
to

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:37.589
stay healthy until a new medication comes
out.

00:51:37.589 --> 00:51:40.640
So
it's buying time for a large number of people.

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:42.940
So
there are a large number of common diseases.

00:51:42.940 --> 00:51:46.730
It
also falls into a spectrum of autoimmune diseases,

00:51:46.730 --> 00:51:53.700
blood clotting disorders, a lot of useful
information that unfortunately a lot of people

00:51:53.700 --> 00:51:57.260
think
that it's just cystic fibrosis or it's just

00:51:57.260 --> 00:52:00.240
Tay-Sach's
disease or it's just the dilated cardiomyopathy

00:52:00.240 --> 00:52:01.240
that
I mentioned.

00:52:01.240 --> 00:52:04.859
But just recently, it really has
expanded out to include a large number of

00:52:04.859 --> 00:52:06.450
actionable
common diseases.

00:52:06.450 --> 00:52:07.450
Yes?

00:52:07.450 --> 00:52:13.079
&gt;&gt;Female #1: I'm curious to know how static
is a

00:52:13.079 --> 00:52:15.190
person's genetic profile as they grow, as
they

00:52:15.190 --> 00:52:18.720
age -- does it change or once you've taken
the

00:52:18.720 --> 00:52:21.110
profile of a person when they're a baby, does
that

00:52:21.110 --> 00:52:23.380
still hold when they're older?

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:28.000
&gt;&gt;Dr. Colby: So the question is, "Does the
genetic

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.069
makeup of a person -- the genetic profile
-- does

00:52:30.069 --> 00:52:32.319
that change with age?"

00:52:32.319 --> 00:52:34.950
So we mentioned the example
of baby Emily.

00:52:34.950 --> 00:52:36.990
She had that genetic testing when
she was a baby.

00:52:36.990 --> 00:52:41.970
If she had genetic testing again
when she was 50 years old, would that information

00:52:41.970 --> 00:52:42.970
change?

00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:44.210
Would that raw data change?

00:52:44.210 --> 00:52:48.069
And the raw
data -- so the letters themselves -- do not

00:52:48.069 --> 00:52:49.069
change.

00:52:49.069 --> 00:52:50.560
At the moment of conception on the moment
of

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:54.970
death -- those raw data, those letters -- of
the genetic code

00:52:54.970 --> 00:52:56.010
are the same.

00:52:56.010 --> 00:53:02.390
Those things around our genes that
turn our genes on and off -- those change.

00:53:02.390 --> 00:53:03.940
It's
called the epigenome.

00:53:03.940 --> 00:53:07.500
The epigenetics but the raw
data -- what we're able to acquire now with

00:53:07.500 --> 00:53:10.760
the DNA
chip with whole genome sequencing -- that

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:12.890
does not
change.

00:53:12.890 --> 00:53:17.309
So with whole genome sequencing, if we
sequence a newborn, we get those 6 billion

00:53:17.309 --> 00:53:20.609
letters,
they really never need to have a similar type

00:53:20.609 --> 00:53:23.150
of
genetic test again.

00:53:23.150 --> 00:53:24.700
We have all that data.

00:53:24.700 --> 00:53:25.700
It's
all there.

00:53:25.700 --> 00:53:28.809
Now it all comes down to analysis and
reporting of that information.

00:53:28.809 --> 00:53:33.279
Female #1: The other question is will their
propensity to certain diseases change because

00:53:33.279 --> 00:53:38.300
certain markers come on and off based on certain
environmental factors they're dealing with?

00:53:38.300 --> 00:53:42.160
&gt;&gt;Dr. Colby: So so the propensity for disease
based

00:53:42.160 --> 00:53:46.140
upon just the raw data will not change.

00:53:46.140 --> 00:53:49.579
But their
propensity will change because almost all

00:53:49.579 --> 00:53:53.230
of these
common diseases -- heart disease, the cancers,

00:53:53.230 --> 00:53:57.170
Alzheimer's -- it's not either only genes
or only

00:53:57.170 --> 00:53:59.390
environment, it's a combination.

00:53:59.390 --> 00:54:03.359
So by learning
about our genetic risks, we're able to modify

00:54:03.359 --> 00:54:07.180
our
non-genetic risk factors -- lifestyle, medications,

00:54:07.180 --> 00:54:10.369
foods we eat, exercises we do.

00:54:10.369 --> 00:54:14.109
So that will change
the total risk.

00:54:14.109 --> 00:54:19.579
Now, people though -- let's say a
person goes and smokes -- that will turn on

00:54:19.579 --> 00:54:23.880
and off
certain genes that are protecting or increasing

00:54:23.880 --> 00:54:25.529
a
person's risk of cancer.

00:54:25.529 --> 00:54:29.619
So they can modify if
genes turn on and off, but not the raw data

00:54:29.619 --> 00:54:31.410
-- not
those letters themselves.

00:54:31.410 --> 00:54:33.220
That is going to stay
the same.

00:54:33.220 --> 00:54:37.099
Male #2: My question is around the accuracy
of

00:54:37.099 --> 00:54:40.619
genetic testing and actually identifying whether
something that somebody

00:54:40.619 --> 00:54:45.940
is predisposed to is going to manifest
itself versus somebody who's not predisposed

00:54:45.940 --> 00:54:47.130
to it
genetic testing will come out.

00:54:47.130 --> 00:54:51.309
So if you took ten people identified
through tests testing that might have something,

00:54:51.309 --> 00:54:53.769
what's the likelihood that they actually end
up showing it

00:54:53.769 --> 00:54:54.900
versus ten random people?

00:54:54.900 --> 00:54:55.900
&gt;&gt;Dr. Colby: Right.

00:54:55.900 --> 00:55:00.329
So the question is about the
accuracy of genetic testing data.

00:55:00.329 --> 00:55:02.779
Are these
predictions that are being made -- those risk

00:55:02.779 --> 00:55:05.440
predictions -- how accurate are they?

00:55:05.440 --> 00:55:09.200
And the
accuracy is really disease dependent -- disease

00:55:09.200 --> 00:55:10.829
or
trait dependent.

00:55:10.829 --> 00:55:15.849
It differs depending on the amount
of research that's been conducted about those

00:55:15.849 --> 00:55:18.980
genes
that are associated with that disease.

00:55:18.980 --> 00:55:22.130
So for
diseases like heart attack or diseases like

00:55:22.130 --> 00:55:25.049
Alzheimer's, for many types of cancer or even
many

00:55:25.049 --> 00:55:27.960
types of autoimmune diseases, the accuracy
is very

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:29.670
high right now.

00:55:29.670 --> 00:55:34.550
For other diseases like brain cancer,
pancreatic cancer -- different types of the

00:55:34.550 --> 00:55:37.980
rarer
cancers -- the accuracy is quite low.

00:55:37.980 --> 00:55:41.190
That we only
have a few markers and is they're not very

00:55:41.190 --> 00:55:42.190
predictive.

00:55:42.190 --> 00:55:46.359
Now, it's true that over time these
predictions are going to only improve.

00:55:46.359 --> 00:55:48.549
That we're
going to learn that there are more genes.

00:55:48.549 --> 00:55:51.160
We're
going to integrate that into the analysis.

00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:53.339
So the
analysis is going to change.

00:55:53.339 --> 00:55:58.230
But that's true of all of
medicine, that there's no component on medicine

00:55:58.230 --> 00:56:01.589
that
is locked, that is concrete.

00:56:01.589 --> 00:56:02.609
Medicine is always
changing.

00:56:02.609 --> 00:56:03.609
It's always evolving.

00:56:03.609 --> 00:56:06.599
And genetics and predictive
medicine is no different.

00:56:06.599 --> 00:56:13.070
And as an example, CPR
was practiced one way for about 100 years.

00:56:13.070 --> 00:56:15.590
And just
recently it came out that that was not the

00:56:15.590 --> 00:56:16.590
correct
way.

00:56:16.590 --> 00:56:18.140
That it could be done better.

00:56:18.140 --> 00:56:21.539
So CPR
guidelines were completely modified.

00:56:21.539 --> 00:56:23.960
And now, that
old way is no more.

00:56:23.960 --> 00:56:26.609
And we have a new method for
CPR.

00:56:26.609 --> 00:56:28.710
So that doesn't mean that CPR -- all the people
who

00:56:28.710 --> 00:56:31.980
were performing CPR in the 60s and 70s and
80s

00:56:31.980 --> 00:56:34.180
should have never been doing it.

00:56:34.180 --> 00:56:37.410
It just means that,
as part of medicine, things are going to improve

00:56:37.410 --> 00:56:40.021
and
they're going to get better as new research

00:56:40.021 --> 00:56:41.021
comes
out.

00:56:41.021 --> 00:56:45.819
That will certainly happen with genetic
testing as well.

